V{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\u000a'''Anandavardhana''' (820\u2013890) was the author of ''Dhvanyaloka'', a work articulating the philosophy of "aesthetic suggestion". The philosopher [[Abhinavagupta]] wrote an important commentary on it.\u000a\u000aAnandavardhana is credited with creating the ''dhvani'' theory. He wrote of ''dhvani'' (meaning sound, or [[resonance]]) in regard to the "soul of poetry."<ref name = "premnath_p11">{{Citation| last = Premnath | first = Devadasan  | last2  = Foskett (Ed.) | first2 = Mary | last3 = Kuan (Ed.) | first3 = Kah-Jin | title = Ways of Being, Ways of Reading: Asian American Biblical Interpretation | publisher = Chalice Press | date = 15 November 2006 | pages = 11 | isbn = 978-0-8272-4254-8}}</ref> "When the poet writes," said Anandavardhana, "he creates a resonant field of emotions."  To understand the poetry, the reader or hearer must be on the same "[[wavelength]]."  The method requires sensitivity on the parts of the writer and the reader.<ref name = "premnath_p11"/> The complete ''Dhvanyaloka'' together with Abhinavagupta's commentary on it has been translated into English by the eminent sanskritist [[Daniel H. H. Ingalls, Sr.|Daniel H.H. Ingalls]] and his collaborators.<ref>{{citation | title = The Dhvanyaloka of Anandavardhana with the Locana of Abhinavagupta |author1=Anandavardhana |author2=Abhinavagupta|author3=Daniel H.H. Ingalls|author4=J.M. Masson|author5=M.V.Patwardhan|publisher=[[Harvard Oriental Series]]}}</ref>\u000a\u000a==Assessment by Modern Sanskritists==\u000aModern Sanskritists have a very high opinion of Anandavardhana. Commenting on Anandavardhana's ''Dhvanyaloka'', [[Pandurang Vaman Kane|P.V. Kane]] writes that  "the Dhvanyaloka is an epoch-making work in the history of Alankara literature. It occupies the same position in poetics as Panini's Ashadhyayi in grammar and Sankracarya's commentary on Vedanta".<ref>P. N. K Bamzai, [http://www.koausa.org/Vitasta/1a.html "Kashmir\u2014The Home of Sanskrit Language and Literature"]. Kashmiri Overseas Assoc.</ref> And [[Daniel H. H. Ingalls, Sr.|Daniel H.H. Ingalls]] calls Anandavardhana 'the most brilliant of all Sanskrit critics'.<ref>{{citation | title = An Anthology of Sanskrit Court Poetry |author1=Vidyakara | author2=Daniel H.H. Ingalls|publisher=Harvard Oriental Series|page=48}}</ref>\u000a\u000a== References ==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a== External links ==\u000a*Bamzai, P. M. K. [http://www.koausa.org/Vitasta/1a.html ''Kashmir \u2013 The Home of Sanskrit Language and Literature'']. Retrieved on 15 November 2008.\u000a*[http://www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674202788 The ''Dhvanyaloka'' of Anandavardhana with the ''Locana'' of Abhinavagupta] (for purchase only).\u000a*revised [http://gretil.sub.uni-goettingen.de/gretil.htm#Alamk GRETIL e-text] (untranslated) of the ''Dhvany\u0101loka'', based on the edition by K. Krishnamoorthy, Delhi: Motilal Banarsidass, 1982.\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Anandavardhana}}\u000a[[Category:9th-century Indian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Indian male philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:9th-century Indian poets]]\u000a[[Category:Kashmiri people]]\u000a[[Category:Kashmiri writers]]\u000a[[Category:820 births]]\u000a[[Category:890 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:Indian male poets]]\u000a\u000a{{india-philosopher-stub}}
